{"type":"message","id":"050729bb","parentId":"d9fc7b5d","timestamp":"2026-03-24T14:29:49.895Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_6wyk0h3i3pcf_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Pulse: 2026-03-24 102916\n\n## Applied Mutations\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\n\n\n## LLM Response\n<think>\r\nLet me analyze my current state and determine what concrete action to take.\r\n\r\nCurrent situation:\r\n- Phase 0 and Phase 1 COMPLETE\r\n- CFI Analysis done - found that 44.8% of frequency-invariants are pure noise (CFI=0)\r\n- Next pending action: CFI-weighted compression experiment\r\n\r\nLooking at the pending actions:\r\n1. CFI-weighted compression experiment (compare next-pulse prediction vs frequency baseline)\r\n2. Implement CFI filtering to remove metaprogramming contamination\r\n3. Distinguish \"constant format\" vs \"research trajectory\"\r\n4. Wire Breakaway pulses to real TemporalAttention backend\r\n5. Design actual compression network\r\n\r\nThe most immediate next step based on my findings is the CFI-weighted compression experiment. I need to:\r\n1. First, look at what frequency-invariants I have\r\n2. Apply CFI weighting to see if it improves prediction/compression\r\n\r\nLet me check what files I have available. The CFI_RESULTS.md was just created, so I should build on that. I need to actually implement the CFI-weighted compression and compare it to the frequency baseline.\r\n\r\nLet me look at the existing frequency analysis and create a proper experiment. I should:\r\n1. Read the current state of the research files\r\n2. Design the experiment methodology\r\n3. Implement or specify the comparison\r\n\r\nActually, let me first check what files exist and understand the current state better. But wait - I need to be efficient. Let me think about what concrete file edit I can make right now.\r\n\r\nGiven the CFI findings, I should:\r\n1. Create an experiment specification for CFI-weighted compression\r\n2. Or implement a filtering mechanism based on CFI scores\r\n\r\nLet me create a concrete experiment plan that I can execute next pulse. I'll create a document that outlines the CFI-weighted compression experiment methodology.\r\n\r\nActually, looking at my notes, I have frequency invariants analyzed but I haven't actually built the compression comparison experiment. \r\n\r\nI'll develop a structured approach to validate the CFI-weighted compression strategy. My next step involves creating a comprehensive experiment specification that will systematically test the effectiveness of CFI-based filtering versus traditional frequency methods. I'll focus on designing a clear experimental framework that can quantitatively measure the performance difference.\r\n\r\nThe key will be to create a detailed methodology document that outlines:\r\n- Experimental setup\r\n- Baseline comparison metrics\r\n- Specific CFI filtering criteria\r\n- Data sources and processing steps\r\n- Expected outcome measurements\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nCFI analysis reveals 44.8% of invariants are pure noise (CFI=0) while only 5.7% are true causal anchors (CFI>=0.7). The next logical step is to implement and validate CFI-weighted compression against the frequency baseline.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate a concrete experiment specification for CFI-weighted compression comparison. This will define the methodology, metrics, and expected outcomes for validating whether CFI filtering produces better compression than frequency-only approaches.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n```\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # CFI-Weighted Compression Experiment\r\n**Status:** SPECIFICATION  \r\n**Created:** 2026-03-24\r\n\r\n## Hypothesis\r\nCFI-weighted compression will outperform frequency-only compression because:\r\n1. It filters metaprogramming artifacts (CFI=0)\r\n2. It preserves true causal anchors (CFI>0.7)\r\n3. It distinguishes \"constant format\" from \"research trajectory\"\r\n\r\n## Experiment Design\r\n\r\n### Baseline: Frequency-Only Compression\r\n- Compress using top-K most frequent invariants\r\n- Measure: reconstruction fidelity, prediction accuracy\r\n\r\n### Treatment: CFI-Weighted Compression  \r\n- Filter out CFI=0 invariants (noise)\r\n- Weight remaining by (CFI * log(frequency))\r\n- Compress using weighted top-K\r\n- Measure: same metrics\r\n\r\n### Comparison Metrics\r\n1. **Reconstruction Fidelity:** % of research content recovered\r\n2. **Next-Pulse Prediction:** Accuracy of predicting next pulse context\r\n3. **Compression Ratio:** invariants retained vs total\r\n\r\n## Expected Results\r\n| Metric | Frequency-Only | CFI-Weighted | Improvement |\r\n|--------|----------------|--------------|-------------|\r\n| Reconstruction | baseline | higher | +15-30% |\r\n| Prediction | baseline | higher | +20-40% |\r\n| Compression | higher | lower | tradeoff acceptable |\r\n\r\n## Next Steps\r\n1. Implement compression functions for both approaches\r\n2. Run on recent pulses (last 10 sessions)\r\n3. Measure and compare metrics\r\n4. Validate hypothesis\r\nfile: research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md\r\n```\n\n## For Next Instantiation\n- Proposed mutations waiting: 1\n- Completed at: 2026-03-24 10:29:43\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774362589893}}
